{"parentUuid":"54e2eb7e-a696-437e-8235-1ff01e5a2f1b","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a12db5ed54240f2d0","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01UmiaCd7vi197cQ5jaLrVFg","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"verifier's law Jason Wei asymmetry of verification\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Asymmetry of verification and verifier’s law by Jason Wei Asymmetry of verification is the idea that some tasks are much easier to verify than to solve. With reinforcement learning (RL) that finally works in a general sense, asymmetry of verification is becoming one of the most important ideas in AI. https://www.jasonwei.net/blog/asymmetry-of-verification-and-verifiers-law\",\"url\":\"https://www.threads.com/@sung.kim.mw/post/DMJrL9vSPGj/asymmetry-of-verification-and-verifiers-law-by-jason-weiasymmetry-of-verificatio\"},{\"title\":\"Asymmetry of verification and verifier’s law (Jason Wei) - YouTube\",\"url\":\"https://www.youtube.com/shorts/xz38mya1XEI\"},{\"title\":\"Jason Wei on X: \\\"New blog post about asymmetry of verification and \\\"verifier's law\\\": https://t.co/bvS8HrX1jP Asymmetry of verification–the idea that some tasks are much easier to verify than to solve–is becoming an important idea as we have RL that finally works generally. Great examples of https://t.co/aQz7N44WCX\\\" / X\",\"url\":\"https://x.com/_jasonwei/status/1945287045251052007\"},{\"title\":\"Asymmetry of verification and verifier’s rule — Jason Wei\",\"url\":\"https://www.jasonwei.net/blog/asymmetry-of-verification-and-verifiers-law\"},{\"title\":\"Verifier’s Law: What Top AI Labs Know That You Don’t | by KellyOnTech | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://kellyontech.medium.com/verifiers-law-what-top-ai-labs-know-that-you-don-t-7ce06a314d16\"},{\"title\":\"Asymmetry of verification in Legal AI\",\"url\":\"https://www.contractken.com/post/asymmetry-of-verification\"},{\"title\":\"Finding Your AI Edge: The Asymmetry of Verification\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@mercsnotes/finding-your-ai-edge-the-asymmetry-of-verification-29f141408e45\"},{\"title\":\"Jason Wei's 3 Laws of AI: A Future Framework for 2025 | LLM Practical Experience Hub\",\"url\":\"https://langcopilot.com/posts/2025-11-08-jason-weis-3-laws-ai-future\"},{\"title\":\"Variation in Verification: Understanding Verification Dynamics in Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2509.17995v1\"},{\"title\":\"Asymmetry of Verification | Founder Collective\",\"url\":\"https://foundercollective.com/blog/asymmetry-of-verification/\"}]\n\nI've found comprehensive information about verifier's law and the asymmetry of verification by Jason Wei. Here's what I found:\n\n## Core Concept\n\nAsymmetry of verification is the idea that some tasks are much easier to verify than to solve. With reinforcement learning (RL) that finally works in a general sense, asymmetry of verification is becoming one of the most important ideas in AI.\n\n## Verifier's Law\n\nVerifier's rule states: The ease of training AI to solve a task is proportional to how verifiable the task is. In simpler terms, if a machine can be trained to judge whether an output is good or bad — quickly, accurately, and at scale — it will master that task faster than we expect.\n\n## Examples\n\nSudoku and crossword puzzles take a lot of time to solve because you have to try many candidates against various constraints, but it is trivial to check if any given solution is correct. Writing the code to operate a website like instagram takes a team of engineers many years, but verifying whether the website is working properly can be done quickly by any layperson.\n\n## Inverse Asymmetry\n\nInterestingly, there are also some tasks that can take way longer to verify than to propose a solution, such as fact-checking all statements in an essay. Many scientific hypotheses are also harder to verify than to come up with, for example, it is easy to state a novel diet but it would take years to verify whether the diet is beneficial for a general population.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"3fe53ceb-f085-4aba-bfd7-241348163cc5","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:37.208Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"verifier's law Jason Wei asymmetry of verification","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01RgqcFMRNpQRDqxFMGsFZ2c","content":[{"title":"Asymmetry of verification and verifier’s law by Jason Wei Asymmetry of verification is the idea that some tasks are much easier to verify than to solve. With reinforcement learning (RL) that finally works in a general sense, asymmetry of verification is becoming one of the most important ideas in AI. https://www.jasonwei.net/blog/asymmetry-of-verification-and-verifiers-law","url":"https://www.threads.com/@sung.kim.mw/post/DMJrL9vSPGj/asymmetry-of-verification-and-verifiers-law-by-jason-weiasymmetry-of-verificatio"},{"title":"Asymmetry of verification and verifier’s law (Jason Wei) - YouTube","url":"https://www.youtube.com/shorts/xz38mya1XEI"},{"title":"Jason Wei on X: \"New blog post about asymmetry of verification and \"verifier's law\": https://t.co/bvS8HrX1jP Asymmetry of verification–the idea that some tasks are much easier to verify than to solve–is becoming an important idea as we have RL that finally works generally. Great examples of https://t.co/aQz7N44WCX\" / X","url":"https://x.com/_jasonwei/status/1945287045251052007"},{"title":"Asymmetry of verification and verifier’s rule — Jason Wei","url":"https://www.jasonwei.net/blog/asymmetry-of-verification-and-verifiers-law"},{"title":"Verifier’s Law: What Top AI Labs Know That You Don’t | by KellyOnTech | Medium","url":"https://kellyontech.medium.com/verifiers-law-what-top-ai-labs-know-that-you-don-t-7ce06a314d16"},{"title":"Asymmetry of verification in Legal AI","url":"https://www.contractken.com/post/asymmetry-of-verification"},{"title":"Finding Your AI Edge: The Asymmetry of Verification","url":"https://medium.com/@mercsnotes/finding-your-ai-edge-the-asymmetry-of-verification-29f141408e45"},{"title":"Jason Wei's 3 Laws of AI: A Future Framework for 2025 | LLM Practical Experience Hub","url":"https://langcopilot.com/posts/2025-11-08-jason-weis-3-laws-ai-future"},{"title":"Variation in Verification: Understanding Verification Dynamics in Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2509.17995v1"},{"title":"Asymmetry of Verification | Founder Collective","url":"https://foundercollective.com/blog/asymmetry-of-verification/"}]},"I've found comprehensive information about verifier's law and the asymmetry of verification by Jason Wei. Here's what I found:\n\n## Core Concept\n\nAsymmetry of verification is the idea that some tasks are much easier to verify than to solve. With reinforcement learning (RL) that finally works in a general sense, asymmetry of verification is becoming one of the most important ideas in AI.\n\n## Verifier's Law\n\nVerifier's rule states: The ease of training AI to solve a task is proportional to how verifiable the task is. In simpler terms, if a machine can be trained to judge whether an output is good or bad — quickly, accurately, and at scale — it will master that task faster than we expect.\n\n## Examples\n\nSudoku and crossword puzzles take a lot of time to solve because you have to try many candidates against various constraints, but it is trivial to check if any given solution is correct. Writing the code to operate a website like instagram takes a team of engineers many years, but verifying whether the website is working properly can be done quickly by any layperson.\n\n## Inverse Asymmetry\n\nInterestingly, there are also some tasks that can take way longer to verify than to propose a solution, such as fact-checking all statements in an essay. Many scientific hypotheses are also harder to verify than to come up with, for example, it is easy to state a novel diet but it would take years to verify whether the diet is beneficial for a general population."],"durationSeconds":9.623694583000615,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"54e2eb7e-a696-437e-8235-1ff01e5a2f1b","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"37324e10-2df4-4154-b7ff-800029ff50c8","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a12db5ed54240f2d0","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TLkqgpZu5tqNcfHHNQwMLc","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Aschenbrenner situational awareness recursive self-improvement automated AI research\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Situational Awareness—The Decade Ahead - A Reflection on Leopold Aschenbrenner’s 2024 Essay - Kingy AI\",\"url\":\"https://kingy.ai/blog/situational-awareness-the-decade-ahead-a-reflection-on-leopold-aschenbrenners-2024-essay/\"},{\"title\":\"Retrospective Book Review: Situational Awareness - AGI Friday\",\"url\":\"https://agifriday.substack.com/p/aschenbrenner\"},{\"title\":\"Situational Awareness: The Decade Ahead - Book Summary and Action Steps\",\"url\":\"https://www.cdebassa.com/notes/situational-awareness-the-decade-ahead\"},{\"title\":\"Leopold Aschenbrenner: Situational Awareness - Stanford Digital Economy Lab\",\"url\":\"https://digitaleconomy.stanford.edu/event/leopold-aschenbrenner-situational-awareness/\"},{\"title\":\"The three main doctrines on the future of AI\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.20050\"},{\"title\":\"Leopold Aschenbrenner: The Visionary Behind a $5.5B AI Revolution\",\"url\":\"https://phemex.com/academy/who-is-leopold-aschenbrenner\"},{\"title\":\"Leopold Aschenbrenner’s “Situational Awareness” Became Silicon Valley’s Most Talked About AI Warning\",\"url\":\"https://www.rebellionresearch.com/leopold-aschenbrenners-situational-awareness-became-silicon-valleys-most-talked-about-ai-warning\"},{\"title\":\"The Novelty Bottleneck: A Framework for Understanding Human Effort Scaling in AI-Assisted Work\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.27438\"},{\"title\":\"Introduction - SITUATIONAL AWARENESS: The Decade Ahead\",\"url\":\"https://situational-awareness.ai/\"}]\n\nI found comprehensive information about Leopold Aschenbrenner's work on these topics. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Overview\n\nLeopold Aschenbrenner refers to \"situational awareness\" as the capacity to recognize where AI technology is actually heading based on empirical signals, and to understand that AGI may arrive well before most institutions are prepared.\n\n## Recursive Self-Improvement and Automated AI Research\n\nAschenbrenner identifies \"recursive self-improvement\" as a core phenomenon: if you can automate the generation of training data that surpasses the best humans, you can push skill to superhuman levels with alarming speed.\n\nA common element of this doctrine is the belief that as progress continues, AI systems themselves will be able to perform most or all of the work required to further advance AI research, commonly referred to as \"Automated AI R&D\", \"Recursive self-improvement\" or \"Intelligence recursion\".\n\n## The Intelligence Explosion\n\nHundreds of millions of AGIs could automate AI research, compressing a decade of algorithmic progress (5+ OOMs) into ≤1 year. Aschenbrenner argues that this could compress a decade of algorithmic progress into less than a year.\n\nAGI by 2027 is strikingly plausible. AI progress won't stop at human-level, and we would rapidly go from human-level to vastly superhuman AI systems.\n\n## Key Background\n\nAschenbrenner worked on the Superalignment team at OpenAI. His 2024 series \"Situational Awareness\" presented a sweeping argument that humanity may be entering the final years before Artificial General Intelligence arrives.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"810c68c8-233f-4e41-a47f-77691f2000b4","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:37.428Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Aschenbrenner situational awareness recursive self-improvement automated AI research","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01GQcZbseqQEdbq1dfucXSBD","content":[{"title":"Situational Awareness—The Decade Ahead - A Reflection on Leopold Aschenbrenner’s 2024 Essay - Kingy AI","url":"https://kingy.ai/blog/situational-awareness-the-decade-ahead-a-reflection-on-leopold-aschenbrenners-2024-essay/"},{"title":"Retrospective Book Review: Situational Awareness - AGI Friday","url":"https://agifriday.substack.com/p/aschenbrenner"},{"title":"Situational Awareness: The Decade Ahead - Book Summary and Action Steps","url":"https://www.cdebassa.com/notes/situational-awareness-the-decade-ahead"},{"title":"Leopold Aschenbrenner: Situational Awareness - Stanford Digital Economy Lab","url":"https://digitaleconomy.stanford.edu/event/leopold-aschenbrenner-situational-awareness/"},{"title":"The three main doctrines on the future of AI","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.20050"},{"title":"Leopold Aschenbrenner: The Visionary Behind a $5.5B AI Revolution","url":"https://phemex.com/academy/who-is-leopold-aschenbrenner"},{"title":"Leopold Aschenbrenner’s “Situational Awareness” Became Silicon Valley’s Most Talked About AI Warning","url":"https://www.rebellionresearch.com/leopold-aschenbrenners-situational-awareness-became-silicon-valleys-most-talked-about-ai-warning"},{"title":"The Novelty Bottleneck: A Framework for Understanding Human Effort Scaling in AI-Assisted Work","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.27438"},{"title":"Introduction - SITUATIONAL AWARENESS: The Decade Ahead","url":"https://situational-awareness.ai/"}]},"I found comprehensive information about Leopold Aschenbrenner's work on these topics. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Overview\n\nLeopold Aschenbrenner refers to \"situational awareness\" as the capacity to recognize where AI technology is actually heading based on empirical signals, and to understand that AGI may arrive well before most institutions are prepared.\n\n## Recursive Self-Improvement and Automated AI Research\n\nAschenbrenner identifies \"recursive self-improvement\" as a core phenomenon: if you can automate the generation of training data that surpasses the best humans, you can push skill to superhuman levels with alarming speed.\n\nA common element of this doctrine is the belief that as progress continues, AI systems themselves will be able to perform most or all of the work required to further advance AI research, commonly referred to as \"Automated AI R&D\", \"Recursive self-improvement\" or \"Intelligence recursion\".\n\n## The Intelligence Explosion\n\nHundreds of millions of AGIs could automate AI research, compressing a decade of algorithmic progress (5+ OOMs) into ≤1 year. Aschenbrenner argues that this could compress a decade of algorithmic progress into less than a year.\n\nAGI by 2027 is strikingly plausible. AI progress won't stop at human-level, and we would rapidly go from human-level to vastly superhuman AI systems.\n\n## Key Background\n\nAschenbrenner worked on the Superalignment team at OpenAI. His 2024 series \"Situational Awareness\" presented a sweeping argument that humanity may be entering the final years before Artificial General Intelligence arrives."],"durationSeconds":8.431117417000234,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"37324e10-2df4-4154-b7ff-800029ff50c8","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"8b52b11b-9ae2-4572-b875-3799e0b926f7","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a12db5ed54240f2d0","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MhtLipjxnWSndSNVnvLhgi","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"verification easier than generation LLM generation-verification gap\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"MIND THE GAP: EXAMINING THE SELF-IMPROVEMENT ...\",\"url\":\"https://proceedings.iclr.cc/paper_files/paper/2025/file/63943ee9fe347f3d95892cf87d9a42e6-Paper-Conference.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"LLM Verification Loops: Best Practices and Patterns | by Tim Williams | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://timjwilliams.medium.com/llm-verification-loops-best-practices-and-patterns-07541c854fd8\"},{\"title\":\"Shrinking the Generation-Verification Gap with Weak Verifiers\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.18203v1\"},{\"title\":\"Weaver: Closing the Generation-Verification Gap with Weak Verifiers · Hazy Research\",\"url\":\"https://hazyresearch.stanford.edu/blog/2025-06-18-weaver\"},{\"title\":\"[2402.08115] On the Self-Verification Limitations of Large Language Models on Reasoning and Planning Tasks\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2402.08115\"},{\"title\":\"Alignment as Distribution Learning: Your Preference Model is Explicitly a Language Model\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.01523\"},{\"title\":\"The New Asymmetry: When Generation Outpaces Verification in AI-Native Development · Derick Chen\",\"url\":\"https://www.buildwithdc.co/posts/the-new-asymmetry-when-generation-outpaces-verification-in-ai-native-development/\"},{\"title\":\"Can Large Reasoning Models Self-Train?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.21444\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about the generation-verification gap in LLMs:\n\n## Core Concept\n\nThe primary objective of self-improvement is predicated on the assumption that \"verification is easier than generation\". This is a fundamental principle underlying recent LLM research.\n\n## Empirical Evidence\n\nLLMs are measurably better at verifying content than generating it, and research consistently shows that LLMs can spot errors in existing content more reliably than they can avoid making those errors during generation.\n\n## Technical Implications\n\nIn the absence of additional resources like labeled data or an external oracle, models can utilize their own verification capabilities, which is particularly effective if the model is more proficient at verification than generation.\n\n## Practical Applications\n\nThe generation-verification gap has enabled new approaches like:\n\n- Weaver, which closes the generation-verification gap without fine-tuning, significant human labeling, or architectural changes by aggregating weak, unlabeled verifier signals using weak supervision\n\n- LLMs can utilize this gap as a learning signal to improve their average accuracy through techniques like majority voting\n\n## Formal Definition\n\nThe generator-verifier gap informally states that verifying whether a given answer is correct or not is easier than generating a correct answer, and such a gap implies that verification is easier to learn than generation from a learning-theoretic perspective.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"745d7b12-e34e-4cb1-931e-fa99d3802e34","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:37.567Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"verification easier than generation LLM generation-verification gap","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_018GLusEuzxSTHfZFZRnk8cr","content":[{"title":"MIND THE GAP: EXAMINING THE SELF-IMPROVEMENT ...","url":"https://proceedings.iclr.cc/paper_files/paper/2025/file/63943ee9fe347f3d95892cf87d9a42e6-Paper-Conference.pdf"},{"title":"LLM Verification Loops: Best Practices and Patterns | by Tim Williams | Medium","url":"https://timjwilliams.medium.com/llm-verification-loops-best-practices-and-patterns-07541c854fd8"},{"title":"Shrinking the Generation-Verification Gap with Weak Verifiers","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.18203v1"},{"title":"Weaver: Closing the Generation-Verification Gap with Weak Verifiers · Hazy Research","url":"https://hazyresearch.stanford.edu/blog/2025-06-18-weaver"},{"title":"[2402.08115] On the Self-Verification Limitations of Large Language Models on Reasoning and Planning Tasks","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2402.08115"},{"title":"Alignment as Distribution Learning: Your Preference Model is Explicitly a Language Model","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.01523"},{"title":"The New Asymmetry: When Generation Outpaces Verification in AI-Native Development · Derick Chen","url":"https://www.buildwithdc.co/posts/the-new-asymmetry-when-generation-outpaces-verification-in-ai-native-development/"},{"title":"Can Large Reasoning Models Self-Train?","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.21444"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about the generation-verification gap in LLMs:\n\n## Core Concept\n\nThe primary objective of self-improvement is predicated on the assumption that \"verification is easier than generation\". This is a fundamental principle underlying recent LLM research.\n\n## Empirical Evidence\n\nLLMs are measurably better at verifying content than generating it, and research consistently shows that LLMs can spot errors in existing content more reliably than they can avoid making those errors during generation.\n\n## Technical Implications\n\nIn the absence of additional resources like labeled data or an external oracle, models can utilize their own verification capabilities, which is particularly effective if the model is more proficient at verification than generation.\n\n## Practical Applications\n\nThe generation-verification gap has enabled new approaches like:\n\n- Weaver, which closes the generation-verification gap without fine-tuning, significant human labeling, or architectural changes by aggregating weak, unlabeled verifier signals using weak supervision\n\n- LLMs can utilize this gap as a learning signal to improve their average accuracy through techniques like majority voting\n\n## Formal Definition\n\nThe generator-verifier gap informally states that verifying whether a given answer is correct or not is easier than generating a correct answer, and such a gap implies that verification is easier to learn than generation from a learning-theoretic perspective."],"durationSeconds":8.710588583000005,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"8b52b11b-9ae2-4572-b875-3799e0b926f7","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"47031aeb-7f63-40a3-a579-e15bab823844","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a12db5ed54240f2d0","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DptjR7puCNcDQUCDvUvKLS","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Karpathy reinforcement learning works where verification cheap\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Karpathy's AutoResearch: 630 Lines of Code, 700 Experiments, and the Beginning of the End of Manual ML Research\",\"url\":\"https://myoid.com/karpathy-autoresearch-autonomous-experiments/\"},{\"title\":\"Andrej Karpathy's Verifiability Thesis: Why AI Is Superhuman at Code and Fails at Car Washes | MindStudio\",\"url\":\"https://www.mindstudio.ai/blog/andrej-karpathy-verifiability-thesis-ai-superhuman-code-fails-car-wash\"},{\"title\":\"Andrej Karpathy: AI Writes Flawless Code But Can't Find a Car Wash — The \\\"Jagged Intelligence\\\" Paradox — BigGo Finance\",\"url\":\"https://finance.biggo.com/news/4d3e80894ed787f3\"},{\"title\":\"Reinforcement Learning Made Affordable for Hardware Verification Engineers\",\"url\":\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9696563/\"},{\"title\":\"AI researcher Andrej Karpathy says he's \\\"bearish on reinforcement learning\\\" for LLM training\",\"url\":\"https://the-decoder.com/ai-researcher-andrej-karpathy-says-hes-bearish-on-reinforcement-learning-for-llm-training/\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about Karpathy's work on reinforcement learning and verification:\n\nKarpathy's key insight is that finding an improvement requires enormous compute (hundreds or thousands of failed experiments), but verifying that an improvement works is cheap — just run the training code once and check the metric.\n\nKarpathy argues that frontier labs invest heavily in reinforcement learning environments where outputs can be verified (code, math, chess), while neglecting domains that resist verification (common sense, aesthetics, human judgment).\n\nThe models excel in verifiable domains, where reinforcement learning can optimize against clear metrics. However, outside those domains — humor, nuance, knowing when to ask clarifying questions — \"everything kind of just meanders.\"\n\nThis framework reflects a broader principle: LLMs can easily automate what you can verify. The reinforcement learning process relies on the model producing outputs that get evaluated, with reward signals based on whether the outputs are correct, requiring a verifier that can reliably say \"yes, this is right\" or \"no, this is wrong.\"\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"9ba53b9e-c16a-439e-8410-7a323b89702a","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:37.666Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Karpathy reinforcement learning works where verification cheap","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01A4H7EirxFSCGBC7oTszSGr","content":[{"title":"Karpathy's AutoResearch: 630 Lines of Code, 700 Experiments, and the Beginning of the End of Manual ML Research","url":"https://myoid.com/karpathy-autoresearch-autonomous-experiments/"},{"title":"Andrej Karpathy's Verifiability Thesis: Why AI Is Superhuman at Code and Fails at Car Washes | MindStudio","url":"https://www.mindstudio.ai/blog/andrej-karpathy-verifiability-thesis-ai-superhuman-code-fails-car-wash"},{"title":"Andrej Karpathy: AI Writes Flawless Code But Can't Find a Car Wash — The \"Jagged Intelligence\" Paradox — BigGo Finance","url":"https://finance.biggo.com/news/4d3e80894ed787f3"},{"title":"Reinforcement Learning Made Affordable for Hardware Verification Engineers","url":"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9696563/"},{"title":"AI researcher Andrej Karpathy says he's \"bearish on reinforcement learning\" for LLM training","url":"https://the-decoder.com/ai-researcher-andrej-karpathy-says-hes-bearish-on-reinforcement-learning-for-llm-training/"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about Karpathy's work on reinforcement learning and verification:\n\nKarpathy's key insight is that finding an improvement requires enormous compute (hundreds or thousands of failed experiments), but verifying that an improvement works is cheap — just run the training code once and check the metric.\n\nKarpathy argues that frontier labs invest heavily in reinforcement learning environments where outputs can be verified (code, math, chess), while neglecting domains that resist verification (common sense, aesthetics, human judgment).\n\nThe models excel in verifiable domains, where reinforcement learning can optimize against clear metrics. However, outside those domains — humor, nuance, knowing when to ask clarifying questions — \"everything kind of just meanders.\"\n\nThis framework reflects a broader principle: LLMs can easily automate what you can verify. The reinforcement learning process relies on the model producing outputs that get evaluated, with reward signals based on whether the outputs are correct, requiring a verifier that can reliably say \"yes, this is right\" or \"no, this is wrong.\""],"durationSeconds":8.248737999999896,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"47031aeb-7f63-40a3-a579-e15bab823844","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
