{"parentUuid":"901723b2-23d2-4c6d-984d-b4860a265c09","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b83cd85c-215e-4dfb-b12b-82fa27341e0f","agentId":"a12db5ed54240f2d0","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VDyfWpxhxFuYcnYTziu38A","type":"tool_result","content":"# Quotes on Recursive Self-Improvement and Intelligence Explosion\n\n## On Automated AI Research and the Loop\n\n**On automating AI research specifically:**\n> \"they will be able to do ML research on a computer\"\n\n**On the core mechanism:**\n> \"they would need only to accelerate the existing trendlines of algorithmic progress\"\n\n**On scale of researchers:**\n> \"we'd have more than 100,000x that—furiously working on algorithmic breakthroughs\"\n\n## On Speed of Intelligence Explosion\n\n**On timeline compression:**\n> \"compress a human-decade of algorithmic progress into less than a year (and that seems conservative)\"\n\n**On the qualitative jump:**\n> \"a qualitative jump like that from a preschooler to a smart high schooler, on top of AI systems already as smart as expert AI researchers/engineers\"\n\n## Critical Gap: Verification/Evaluation Bottleneck\n\n**The document does NOT address whether verification or evaluation of AI research progress represents a constraint.** Aschenbrenner discusses compute bottlenecks for experiments, complementarities with humans, and diminishing returns to research effort—but does not examine whether the ability to *verify* or *evaluate* whether proposed improvements actually work could gate the loop, independent of compute availability."}]},"uuid":"d5a8ba03-9cee-4baf-8c12-bb3b3f461f05","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:55.368Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":190158,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Quotes on Recursive Self-Improvement and Intelligence Explosion\n\n## On Automated AI Research and the Loop\n\n**On automating AI research specifically:**\n> \"they will be able to do ML research on a computer\"\n\n**On the core mechanism:**\n> \"they would need only to accelerate the existing trendlines of algorithmic progress\"\n\n**On scale of researchers:**\n> \"we'd have more than 100,000x that—furiously working on algorithmic breakthroughs\"\n\n## On Speed of Intelligence Explosion\n\n**On timeline compression:**\n> \"compress a human-decade of algorithmic progress into less than a year (and that seems conservative)\"\n\n**On the qualitative jump:**\n> \"a qualitative jump like that from a preschooler to a smart high schooler, on top of AI systems already as smart as expert AI researchers/engineers\"\n\n## Critical Gap: Verification/Evaluation Bottleneck\n\n**The document does NOT address whether verification or evaluation of AI research progress represents a constraint.** Aschenbrenner discusses compute bottlenecks for experiments, complementarities with humans, and diminishing returns to research effort—but does not examine whether the ability to *verify* or *evaluate* whether proposed improvements actually work could gate the loop, independent of compute availability.","durationMs":5871,"url":"https://situational-awareness.ai/from-agi-to-superintelligence/"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"901723b2-23d2-4c6d-984d-b4860a265c09","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
